  "prompt": "Why is oxalic acid soluble in water?",
  "response": "Oxalic acid (C\u2082H\u2082O\u2084) is soluble in water due to several factors that influence its solubility:\n\n1. **Polar Nature**: Oxalic acid is a polar molecule. It contains two carboxylic acid groups (-COOH), which can engage in hydrogen bonding with water molecules. This polarity allows the oxalic acid to interact favorably with water, a highly polar solvent.\n\n2. **Hydrogen Bonding**: The presence of hydroxyl (-OH) groups in the carboxylic acid functional groups can form hydrogen bonds with water. This intermolecular attraction helps to pull the oxalic acid molecules into solution.\n\n3. **Dissociation in Water**: Oxalic acid is a diprotic acid, meaning it can donate two protons (H\u207a ions) when dissolved in water. The dissociation into oxalate ions (C\u2082O\u2084\u00b2\u207b) and hydrogen ions (H\u207a) increases the number of particles in solution, enhancing its solubility. The ionic nature of the dissociation products also leads to strong interactions with water.\n\n4. **Thermodynamic Favorability**: The overall process of dissolving oxalic acid in water is thermodynamically favorable. The enthalpy change associated with dissolving and the increase in entropy due to the dispersion of the acid molecules into the solvent contribute to its solubility.\n\nThese factors combine to make oxalic acid quite soluble in water, allowing it to readily dissolve and form a solution.",
